    "Let me analyze the reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nThe reaction SMILES: C1CCOC1.Cc1cc(C)cc(C)c1.Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)[O-])cc1.c1cc[nH+]cc1.Cc1cccc(C(=O)O)c1I.ClCCl.[H-].[Na+]>>Cc1cc(C)c(I2OC(=O)c3cccc(C)c32)c(C)c1\n\nLet me identify each component:\n1. C1CCOC1 - THF (tetrahydrofuran) - solvent\n2. Cc1cc(C)cc(C)c1 - 2,4,6-trimethylbenzene (mesitylene) - reactant\n3. Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)[O-])cc1 - p-toluenesulfonate anion (TsO-) - part of a salt\n4. c1cc[nH+]cc1 - pyridinium cation - part of a salt (pyridinium p-toluenesulfonate = PPTS, a catalyst)\n5. Cc1cccc(C(=O)O)c1I - 2-iodo-4-methylbenzoic acid - reactant\n6. ClCCl - dichloromethane (DCM) - solvent\n7. [H-].[Na+] - sodium hydride (NaH) - reagent/base\n\nThe product is: Cc1cc(C)c(I2OC(=O)c3cccc(C)c32)c(C)c1\n\nThis looks like a lactonization/iodolactonization type reaction where the 2-iodo-4-methylbenzoic acid reacts with mesitylene to form an iodonium lactone product.\n\nLooking at the mapped reaction, the atoms from mesitylene and the 2-iodo-4-methylbenzoic acid end up in the product. The iodine from the benzoic acid forms a bridge (I2OC(=O)) connecting the two aromatic rings.\n\nSo the roles:\n- C1CCOC1 (THF): solvent\n- Cc1cc(C)cc(C)c1 (mesitylene): reactant\n- Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)[O-])cc1.c1cc[nH+]cc1 (PPTS, pyridinium p-toluenesulfonate): catalyst\n- Cc1cccc(C(=O)O)c1I (2-iodo-4-methylbenzoic acid): reactant\n- ClCCl (DCM): solvent\n- [H-].[Na+] (NaH): reagent (base)\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping:\n\nreactants: mesitylene, 2-iodo-4-methylbenzoic acid\nreagents: NaH (base)\ncatalysts: PPTS (pyridinium p-toluenesulfonate)\nsolvents: THF, DCM"
